(Applicable to Warera.io and Associated Discord Roleplay Platforms)

An Act

to define offences, regulate conduct, prescribe punishments, establish judicial procedure, and maintain public order and institutional discipline in a digital roleplay environment; and for matters connected therewith or incidental thereto.

CHAPTER I

PRELIMINARY

Section 1. Short Title and Commencement:

This Act may be called the Judicial Conduct, Discipline, and Community Order Act, 2025. 

Or 

JDC Act,2025.

It shall come into force upon adoption under the authority of the Constitution.

Section 2. Constitutional Authority

This Act is enacted pursuant to the Constitution and shall be read subject to its provisions relating to the Judiciary, discipline, enforcement, and governance.

Section 3. Extent and Application

This Act shall apply to all citizens, officials, officers, judges, military personnel, and participants recognised by the Nation.

Enforcement shall operate through Warera.io mechanics and officially recognised Discord servers.

Section 4. Definitions

Unless otherwise defined, terms used in this Act shall have the meanings assigned to them under the Constitution.

CHAPTER II

CLASSIFICATION OF OFFENCES

Section 5. Levels of Offences

Level 1 – Minor Misconduct

Low-impact behavioural or procedural violations, including first-time or accidental breaches.

Level 2 – Moderate Offences

Repeated or negligent conduct causing disruption or reputational harm.

Level 3 – Serious Offences

Acts materially harming governance, diplomacy, judicial integrity, or national stability.

Level 4 – Extreme or Last-Resort Offences

Persistent, deliberate, or severe violations threatening constitutional order or community cohesion.

CHAPTER III

SPECIFIED OFFENCES

Section 6. Diplomatic and International Offences

The following acts shall constitute offences:

a. Lying about fines, reparations, or diplomatic obligations.
b. Misleading or deceiving foreign nations and authorities.
c. Using hostile or aggressive diplomatic language.
d. Damaging the international reputation of the Nation.
e. Making unauthorised diplomatic statements or commitments.
f. Creating or presenting fake agreements on behalf of the state.
g. Sabotaging negotiations through insults or hostility.
h. Refusing to honour signed agreements or compromises.
i. Publishing harmful or offensive content against other nations.
j. Breaking a Non-Aggression Pact (NAP).

Section 6A. Article-Based Offences

The following acts committed via the Warera.io Article feature shall constitute offences under this Act:

a. Publishing false, misleading, or deceptive content in any Article.
b. Making unauthorised or fake diplomatic statements in an Article.
c. Defaming, insulting, or threatening other nations, officials, or citizens through Articles.
d. Posting content intended to sabotage negotiations, governance, or military operations.
e. Creating Articles that deliberately breach Non-Aggression Pacts, agreements, or constitutional obligations.
f. Using Articles to disclose internal government or confidential information without authorisation.
g. Repeated publication of provocative, hostile, or toxic content in Articles.
h. Manipulating Article content to misrepresent the Government’s position.

Section 7. Government and Internal Conduct Offences

a. Abuse of power for personal or political gain.
b. Wilful neglect of official duties.
c. Disobedience of lawful government orders.
d. Acting beyond one’s assigned role or rank.
e. Refusal to follow established procedures.
f. Interfering with official government deliberations.
g. Leaking internal or confidential information.
h. Overstepping lawful authority.
i. Manipulating governmental processes.
j. Illegally influencing laws, votes, or outcomes.

Section 8. Military and Security Offences

a. Conducting military actions such as issuing any unauthorised Orders.
b. Ignoring lawful defence orders.
c. Negligent miscommunication causing military confusion.
d. Issuing false or harmful military instructions.

Section 9. Behaviour and Public Conduct Offences

a. Harassment or personal insults.
b. Inciting drama or hostility.
c. Publicly spreading false information.
d. Disrespecting officials or institutions.
e. Disruptive emotional outbursts.
f. Defamation of citizens or leaders.
g. Racial, cultural, or religious insults.
h. Bullying or repeated targeted hostility.
i. Toxic behaviour harming community stability.
j. Threatening to leave the nation for manipulation.

Section 10. Court and Legal Offences

a. Lying under oath.
b. Providing false or fabricated evidence.
c. Ignoring or defying a court ruling.
d. Interfering with judicial proceedings.
e. Misleading the judge or concealing information.
f. Refusing to pay court-ordered fines.

CHAPTER IV

RIGHTS OF THE ACCUSED

Section 11. Guaranteed Rights

Every accused person shall have the right to:

a. Defend themselves personally or through representation.
b. Remain silent without adverse inference.
c. Fair, impartial, and respectful treatment.
d. Access to evidence relied upon by the Court.

CHAPTER V

JUDICIAL PROCEDURE

Section 12. Structure of Court Hearings

a. Opening and reminder of decorum.

The Court formally opens the hearing.
Participants are reminded to behave respectfully, follow rules, and maintain proper decorum.
Before proceeding, all judges and participants take the Bhagavad Gita-inspired oath, affirming:

“I shall perform my duty with honesty, fairness, and impartiality; I shall not act out of anger, fear, or personal gain; I shall uphold truth, justice, and the Constitution of the Nation.”

b. Identification of parties and roles.

Each participant states their name and role (e.g., accused, plaintiff, witness, or representative).

c. Neutral case summary.

The Court provides a brief, impartial summary of the case, including key events, prior rulings, and context.

d. Presentation of evidence.

Each side presents evidence clearly and concisely (screenshots, in-game logs, Articles, Discord messages).
Only relevant evidence shall be considered.

e. One formal statement per side.

Each side gives one formal statement summarizing their position.
Statements must be fact-based and relevant, free from personal attacks or emotional language.

f. Judicial questioning.

Judges may ask questions to clarify facts or evidence.
Before questioning, all judges remind themselves of the Bhagavad Gita oath, reaffirming duty and impartiality.
All answers must be truthful and factual.

g. Deliberation and voting led by the Attorney General.

Judge privately deliberate, evaluate evidence, and vote on findings.
The Attorney General ensures fairness and order in the deliberation.

h. Pronouncement of judgment and penalties.

Judges announce the final ruling and penalties, according to offence level.
Decisions are final and binding, unless the Constitution provides otherwise.

Section 13. Finality of Judgments

Judgments under this Act shall be final and binding, except where the Constitution expressly provides otherwise.

CHAPTER VI

PUNISHMENTS AND ENFORCEMENT

Section 14. Punishments by Offence Level

Level 1 – Minor Misconduct

a. Warning or reprimand.
b. Short Discord timeout (up to platform minimums).
C. Fine of 25 coins.

Level 2 – Moderate Offences

a. Formal censure.
b. Discord timeout (extended duration).
c. Temporary suspension from roles.
d. Fine of 50 coins.

Level 3 – Serious Offences

a. Removal from office or authority.
b. Long-term Discord timeout.
c. Disqualification from government or judiciary roles.
d. Fine Of 100 coins.

Level 4 – Extreme Offences

a. Permanent removal from office.
b. Maximum Discord timeout or ban (as permitted).
c. Permanent disqualification from national office participation.
d. Fine Of 200 coins.

Section 15. Discord Timeout as Judicial Penalty

Discord timeouts imposed under this Act shall constitute lawful judicial punishment.
Duration shall be proportionate to offence severity.
Enforcement shall comply with Discord platform limits.

CHAPTER VII

NOT A STATEMENT OF GOVERNMENT.

Section 16. Disclaimer

Any personal statement or communication by an individual shall not be deemed an official statement of the Government unless expressly authorised.
Such statements shall not bind the Nation diplomatically or legally.
This section shall not shield individuals from liability under this Act.

CHAPTER VIII

MISCELLANEOUS

Section 17. Platform Compatibility

This Act shall be interpreted to remain compatible with Warera.io mechanics and Discord rules.

Section 18. Supremacy of the Constitution

In case of inconsistency, the Constitution shall prevail.

Statement of Objects and Reasons

This Act codifies offences, discipline, and judicial enforcement within a digital roleplay nation, ensuring order, fairness, and constitutional supremacy.
